1
00:00:01,768 --> 00:00:30,577
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambodassam Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambodassam Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambodassam Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble,

2
00:00:30,794 --> 00:00:32,676
and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:37,140 --> 00:00:38,060
Put my microphone on.

4
00:00:40,543 --> 00:00:40,844
Okay.

5
00:00:41,744 --> 00:00:50,753
So I thought today we'd tackle a more, a slightly more, for want of a better word, mystical discourse.

6
00:00:50,853 --> 00:00:56,700
And it's called, or it's called after, somebody called Bahia of the Barcloth.

7
00:00:57,101 --> 00:01:11,179
Now, whenever you get people writing about saints and holy people, hagiography, they always, of course, pump it up to make sure that either the person is amazing or the teacher is.

8
00:01:12,003 --> 00:01:20,370
Now, it's not that the Buddha wasn't an amazing teacher, but in order to make him more amazing, we got this story about Bahia.

9
00:01:20,712 --> 00:01:25,075
So he was a merchant and he used to ply up and down the Indian coast.

10
00:01:25,816 --> 00:01:30,040
And one day he was shipwrecked and on a raft he made land.

11
00:01:30,641 --> 00:01:32,763
And suddenly he starts wearing a bark cloth.

12
00:01:33,263 --> 00:01:41,992
Now, for those of you who want to know what a bark cloth is, you have to peel the inner bark off trees and beat it until it's soft.

13
00:01:42,326 --> 00:01:49,518
And then it can be used as a loincloth, skirt, draperies and wall hangings and in thick layers make an excellent bed.

14
00:01:50,358 --> 00:01:51,620
So that's what you can do tomorrow.

15
00:01:52,581 --> 00:01:59,433
But it also says it's an ancient art which is deeply involved in religious and ceremonial life.

16
00:01:59,453 --> 00:02:00,453
So remember that bit.

17
00:02:01,665 --> 00:02:06,561
Anyway, he starts wearing this barcloth and he becomes a mendicant.

18
00:02:06,582 --> 00:02:07,787
And of course, people feed him.

19
00:02:07,826 --> 00:02:12,401
And after a while, he got the impression that, in fact, he was fully liberated.

20
00:02:13,157 --> 00:02:25,336
Well, as these stories go, a god appeared to him, an old relation, and said to him, no, you're not liberated.

21
00:02:25,355 --> 00:02:26,336
You're not enlightened.

22
00:02:26,377 --> 00:02:29,420
In fact, spiritually speaking, you're as thick as a plank.

23
00:02:30,141 --> 00:02:32,825
And the person you want to go and meet is the Buddha.

24
00:02:33,486 --> 00:02:35,751
So, of course, off he goes to meet the Buddha.

25
00:02:35,871 --> 00:02:38,895
He must have been a bit disappointed at that revelation, mind, you know.

26
00:02:41,525 --> 00:02:44,730
Now, when he gets to the Buddha, of course, we'll come to that.

27
00:02:45,413 --> 00:03:00,581
So I think a better story, shall we say, which seems more true, is that the Brahmins were, of course, developing their own scriptures, which were called the Upanishads, translates as sort of connection.

28
00:03:00,602 --> 00:03:04,308
They're also known as the Vedanta, the end of the Vedas.

29
00:03:04,288 --> 00:03:15,486
And they were specifically interested in who we were, what was the ground of our being, right?

30
00:03:15,707 --> 00:03:16,508
Ontology.

31
00:03:17,550 --> 00:03:31,073
So, this is a passage from the Bhadranyaka Upanishad, and this is what it says.

32
00:03:33,989 --> 00:03:48,122
That imperishable is the unseen seer, the unheard hearer, the unthought thinker, the un-understood understander.

33
00:03:49,463 --> 00:04:03,117
Other than it there is naught that sees, other than it there is naught that hears, other than it there is naught that thinks, and other than it there is naught that understands.

34
00:04:03,638 --> 00:04:09,145
In other words, it's pointing to this self, which is transcendent of everything.

35
00:04:10,048 --> 00:04:13,353
But it's interesting to see how it is expressed.

36
00:04:13,733 --> 00:04:20,923
The imperishable, that which does not change, etc., etc., is the unseen seer, right?

37
00:04:20,944 --> 00:04:22,266
The unseen seer.

38
00:04:22,286 --> 00:04:23,588
Okay.

39
00:04:23,608 --> 00:04:28,115
So it's very Zen, you know, like the effortless effort, the unseen seer.

40
00:04:29,336 --> 00:04:29,437
Okay.

41
00:04:29,456 --> 00:04:29,697
Okay.

42
00:04:31,161 --> 00:04:38,432
So this is, now these people who followed this particular Upanishad used to wear the bark cloth, right?

43
00:04:38,451 --> 00:04:46,023
That was their, shall we say, signature dress, just like the Buddhist monks went around with a bald head, right?

44
00:04:46,122 --> 00:04:52,250
Everybody else had long matted hair, dreadlocks, but the Buddha made us shave our heads.

45
00:04:54,213 --> 00:05:00,762
So all these sects had their own little way of manifesting who or what they were following.

46
00:05:02,177 --> 00:05:11,932
So he's obviously heard about the Buddha and he comes to find him and he finds him on alms round.

47
00:05:12,413 --> 00:05:15,038
And the Buddha says, you know, this isn't the time.

48
00:05:16,880 --> 00:05:22,610
And he says, look, I'm a very old man and you're not so young and we could die any moment.

49
00:05:22,769 --> 00:05:25,134
So really, you know, please give me the teaching.

50
00:05:25,314 --> 00:05:27,577
So the Buddha, out of his compassion, does so.

51
00:05:28,485 --> 00:05:39,476
And now as the story goes, not long after he was fully liberated, he got gored by a cow who was looking after her calf, right?

52
00:05:40,098 --> 00:05:42,581
So again, I think we can take that with a little pinch of salt.

53
00:05:44,141 --> 00:05:54,713
Anyway, this is what the Buddha says to him.

54
00:05:55,519 --> 00:05:59,124
Here in Bahia, you should train yourself thus.

55
00:06:00,245 --> 00:06:03,048
In the seen, there is merely the seen.

56
00:06:03,067 --> 00:06:07,892
In the heard, there is merely what is heard.

57
00:06:08,432 --> 00:06:11,976
And in the sensed, there is merely what is sensed.

58
00:06:12,958 --> 00:06:17,182
In the cognized, there is merely what is cognized.

59
00:06:17,202 --> 00:06:19,745
And in this way, you should train yourself, Bahia.

60
00:06:20,565 --> 00:06:24,430
Now, if you're listening to this, you may very well become fully liberated, okay?

61
00:06:26,317 --> 00:06:30,480
Here's the crucial bit.

62
00:06:30,500 --> 00:06:54,466
When Bahía, for you, in the seen there is merely what is seen, in the heard merely what is heard, in the sensed merely what is sensed, and in the cognized is merely what is cognized, then, Bahía, you will not be with that.

63
00:06:55,122 --> 00:07:01,728
When by here you are not with that, then by here you will not be in that.

64
00:07:02,488 --> 00:07:12,437
And when by here you are not in that, then by here you will neither be here nor beyond nor in between the two.

65
00:07:12,778 --> 00:07:15,440
Just this is the end of suffering.

66
00:07:18,423 --> 00:07:19,184
Anybody awaken?

67
00:07:20,586 --> 00:07:21,747
No?

68
00:07:21,766 --> 00:07:23,187
Don't worry, it didn't work for me either.

69
00:07:26,137 --> 00:07:28,360
So now what's the Buddha saying here?

70
00:07:30,663 --> 00:07:31,865
Let me just go back up a bit.

71
00:07:31,985 --> 00:07:32,547
Yes, that's right.

72
00:07:32,826 --> 00:07:34,108
What's the Buddha saying here?

73
00:07:36,372 --> 00:07:40,898
So in Buddhist psychology, we have a sense base.

74
00:07:41,918 --> 00:07:48,228
We have something that the sense base is aware of, or senses, rather, senses.

75
00:07:48,247 --> 00:07:50,511
And there is the awareness, the consciousness.

76
00:07:50,730 --> 00:07:53,074
This consciousness is dependent on

77
00:07:54,252 --> 00:07:55,194
on the sense base.

78
00:07:55,415 --> 00:08:00,947
So that's why the Buddha enumerates consciousnesses according to the sense basis.

79
00:08:01,307 --> 00:08:06,959
So you have eye consciousness, nose consciousness, ear consciousness, etc., etc.

80
00:08:07,281 --> 00:08:07,521
Okay?

81
00:08:08,584 --> 00:08:11,028
So here, what the Buddha is saying is

82
00:08:11,346 --> 00:08:14,350
That in any given experience, there's an object.

83
00:08:14,490 --> 00:08:16,110
It could be a video you're watching.

84
00:08:16,151 --> 00:08:18,994
It could be a biscuit you're eating, whatever.

85
00:08:19,053 --> 00:08:20,074
That's the object.

86
00:08:20,636 --> 00:08:24,139
And he's saying when you are not with that, right?

87
00:08:24,238 --> 00:08:27,622
So that's a connection of being with something.

88
00:08:29,303 --> 00:08:39,413
And when you're not with that, then the sense base, if you're not aware of something through a sense base, then you're not in the sense base.

89
00:08:39,966 --> 00:08:44,692
And if you're not in the sense base, then consciousness cannot arise.

90
00:08:46,654 --> 00:09:08,741
So you're neither there with the object, here with the sense base, and in between with that consciousness, which is a screen upon which these two things arise.

91
00:09:10,460 --> 00:09:22,038
When you experience something beyond that, then you've experienced something which is not part of the psycho-physical organism.

92
00:09:23,100 --> 00:09:25,845
And just this is the awakening.

93
00:09:37,923 --> 00:09:38,104
Yeah?

94
00:09:41,711 --> 00:09:43,899
Now, this is recorded, so I'm not going to repeat it.

95
00:09:44,501 --> 00:09:47,091
I couldn't repeat it anyway, but you've got the idea anyway.

96
00:09:48,758 --> 00:09:50,524
So you can always listen to it again if you want.

97
00:09:52,917 --> 00:09:57,764
Now, the thing is that when Bahiya hears this, he is actually immediately enlightened.

98
00:09:58,044 --> 00:10:00,368
And the Buddha actually gives him a title.

99
00:10:00,708 --> 00:10:04,114
He gave titles to certain disciples who had special gifts.

100
00:10:04,553 --> 00:10:16,572
So, for instance, Sariputta was called the Dhammasenapati, the general of the Dharma, because of his understanding of the Dharma, which was said to be second only to the Buddha.

101
00:10:16,591 --> 00:10:17,552
So he called him.

102
00:10:17,894 --> 00:10:18,995
Wait till I find it.

103
00:10:19,336 --> 00:10:19,937
Where are we?

104
00:10:23,562 --> 00:10:25,645
I'm moving around too much on this page.

105
00:10:30,774 --> 00:10:43,537
Pipabina Tichim, the quickest person to become liberated amongst all those who were quick to become liberated.

106
00:10:44,258 --> 00:10:47,123
That's the title he gave him.

107
00:10:50,461 --> 00:10:57,389
And as I say, later on, as it said, you know, he dies from an attack from a cow.

108
00:10:57,409 --> 00:11:01,794
So now this is the story of Bahir of the Barcloth.

109
00:11:01,815 --> 00:11:06,039
And it fits into the Udana Sutta.

110
00:11:06,200 --> 00:11:10,686
So these are a collection of the inspired verses of the Buddha.

111
00:11:11,427 --> 00:11:19,557
And next week, I'll actually read that discourse and the Buddha's own response in verse, which will add to this meaning.

112
00:11:22,168 --> 00:11:23,990
That's if I explain it correctly.

113
00:11:26,453 --> 00:11:47,855
So I hope that has been of some use, that it has not confused you, and that by your insight meditation, by seeing this process of how we create the world, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

